        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2011-11-04 15:40:16.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Fails\n\nTests received by maloo, run on rhel/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/30578dee-06f9-11e1-9433-52540025f9af).  Ran 13 tests.  1 tests failed: sanityn.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "09362c3d9fa32abea15d40f4540456beed33b034",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-11-04 20:26:47.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: (2 inline comments)\n\nI think there is a much more efficient way to get this information.\n\nAlso, this handles the glimpse case (remote OST access).  Does it also handle the case for local getattr?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "26d54e41e4651e60f6b528e942518b486430a4c0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-11-04 20:55:39.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nNote also that there should be a sanity.sh test that verifies the block count returned by \"ls -l\" is non-zero for a newly written file.  This currently returns 0:\n\n$ cp /etc/hosts /mnt/lustre/foo\n$ ls -l /mnt/lustre/foo | awk '{ print $1 }'\n0",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "2afff46119a0b61cf95131ae7dce05c3ea900e41",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-11-08 03:49:12.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)\n\nIf I understand it correctly, we should do the same thing for ccc_object_glimpse() otherwise if backup tool is running on the other nodes, it still won't get correct ideas about blocks.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "a2277838078a0d8359670d42e2484426042eb371",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-11-08 06:39:17.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nIf there is no simple way to report an accurate block count on the client, then at a minimum it should report an inaccurate block count that is non-zero (e.g. 1 block, like ZFS does) so that cp and tar do not fail.\n\nJinshan, is there some quick check that can be done to detect if there are dirty pages on an inode?  Check in the address space, or if the inode is on a dirty list?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "5b28bfcc61d7eab88c5143cca3e69da67c426f4f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-11-08 07:00:14.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nYes, it's easy to check if an inode is dirty via kernel functions - for example, we can scan address_space radix tree with DIRTY tag. However this is not reliable if there exists write mmap for this file.\n\nI think we can do this after page_mkwrite() is implemented in lustre, where we will set page dirty in ll_page_mkwrite().",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e346449317728c115d378f1cf2e77e1bbd4bd167",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-11-08 16:58:39.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nA temp solution for this problem is to assume i_blocks is not zero if there exists mmap for this inode(by checking cob_mmap_cnt); otherwise we check inode dirty pages or OSC write pending list to determine i_blocks.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "69c75cb1b4fbb91c7426f6d0abc281b54df66580",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-12-13 20:05:54.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThis patch is one that I'd like to include for 2.2, since there is a danger of data loss otherwise.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "553fa4651df6f15b64f8bf6f3bfce1480221572e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 103,
        "name": "Zhenyu Xu",
        "email": "bobijam@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bobijam"
      },
      "date": "2011-12-14 05:50:18.000000000",
      "message": "Uploaded patch set 2.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "6dc08f7c0f41205730eeca2f8c87f5c5dd8c9733",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-12-14 06:47:24.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(2 inline comments)\n\nIt only makes sense to do this check if the size is > 0, not only if the size is == 0.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
